Multiple open-source Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers exist for SendGrid, enabling AI agents to manage email workflows, marketing campaigns, contact lists, and analytics via the SendGrid v3 API [1][2][3][4][5][6]. While features vary by implementation, common capabilities include sending transactional and template-based emails, retrieving performance metrics, and managing suppression lists [2][3][6][7].

To use these servers, you must configure your MCP client—such as Claude Desktop or VS Code extensions like Cline—to execute the server and provide your SendGrid API key via environment variables [1][2][3][5][6]. Most implementations default to a read-only mode for safety [1][2][4]. For example, a basic Claude Desktop configuration looks like this:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "sendgrid": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "sendgrid-mcp"],
      "env": {
        "SENDGRID_API_KEY": "SG.your_api_key_here"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Implementations are available in both Node.js (e.g., `deyikong/sendgrid-mcp`) and Python (e.g., `FINCH285/SendGrid-MCP-Server`) [1][6]. Always verify specific safety features like write-approval tokens or test-mode allowlists in the documentation for your chosen repository [2].
